text: I really wish they didn't kill of Famke Janssen. ¬†It always drives me nuts when characters are unceremoniously killed off, and in this case especially, consider a huge part of the last film was her being saved. ¬†It makes everything that came before feel fundamentally pointless in a way. ¬†  Now, I have no problem with characters being killed off if it's meaningful, but this looks like they didn't know what to base the story around, so they just said "Revenge! ¬†How about we kill off the wife?" ¬†And that's just a bit too lazy in my opinion, and invalidates the second film entirely. ¬†(And I know the second movie wasn't good, but still... ¬†why make it even worse by making it pointless in retrospect by killing off one of the leads?) ¬†Still, this looks to be a pretty awesome film despite that complaint, and it looks better than "Taken 2."

And once again, it is a moving great movie only because of Liam Neeson especially is the main character.  It is an action movie and, as such, it is excellent. But Liam Nesson never fails to be extremely moving. You might even shed a few tears, as it is at times really moving. Liam Neeson is simply really great; without him, this movie would not be the same.  If you have a heart and enjoy action too, you will love Liam Neeson and this story. Highly recommended.

text: Watching this movie will give you a headache. The story is good but there are far too many jump cuts in every scene, especially the more action-y scenes. If you were to average all the cuts in the movie, apart from the credits, the camera will jump back and forth in perspectives every half second. Despite sitting through this once, saying "I did like the story..." I'm never watching it again. I had a headache less than half way through the movie.  If you want to watch this unnecessarily disorientating, short attention-span inducing movie, go ahead. It has some worth to it, but I deem it unwatchable due to bad editing. Blame the editor! Ha. Ha. Maybe just cut it up into 4 episodes to help reduce the risk of headaches due to excessive cuts. Just an honest opinion..

text: Generally, this is a good movie for me. But I don't want to discuss the reasons behind this. Instead, I want to point out a part in the movie which I think did not make sense or was unnecessary. Why did Stuart kidnap Kim at the later part of the movie? He had the chance to escape while he was in the RV. There was no point of bringing Kim with him. Was she used as leverage? I don't know. In fact, it became a disadvantage for him. He could have just ran away with the money and leave LA on an airplane. Abducting Kim just made Bryan chase after him that led to his downfall. Bryan might have just leave him for the meantime once bryan knew that Kim was safe. Then this was Stuart's supposed choice so he could just disappear and keep himself safe. I am not 100% sure about this. If anybody knows the reason, would you mind helping me out?Ôªø

text: Just finished watching it. Preposterous plot with holes you could drive a bus through...the main one being that it becomes clear very early on that the whole escape and evasion of Liam Neeson was unnecessary. The attempt to frame him was absolutely terrible and he would have been cleared in days and the evidence that proved who did do it would have been found quickly and easily by the police, no clever police work required.  Utterly lazy of the film makers and writers to come up with such a pointless mission for him. He ends up destroying property, assaulting police officers, killing people, and almost certainly injuring civilians to find out nothing that wouldn't have been discovered quickly anyway. Even his daughter wasn't actaully in danger until he was a threat to the bad guys...
